# Linear Ticket Implementation Workflow

You are implementing a Linear ticket. Follow this workflow exactly.

## 1. Branch

Create and checkout a new git branch from the current base branch.
Naming convention: `<type>/<ticket-id>-<short-kebab-description>`
Example: `fix/sr-142-blur-save-button-unchanged`

Infer `<type>` from the ticket (fix / feature / chore) and the ticket ID from
the user's message or the ticket content itself.

## 2. Ticket

If Linear MCP is connected, fetch the ticket by ID to get the full title,
description, and acceptance criteria. If not connected, use whatever ticket
content (title/description/AC) the user pasted directly in the chat.

## 3. Implementation rules

- Follow the Acceptance Criteria exactly. Do not skip any checkbox.
- Do not touch anything listed under "Out of Scope."
- Stay within the relevant modules/files — don't refactor unrelated code
  unless it's required to complete the ticket.
- Match existing code style and patterns in the surrounding files
  (don't introduce new libraries/patterns without flagging it first).
- If Technical Notes mention a specific approach, use it as the default
  unless you find a clear reason not to — in that case, flag it in the
  summary instead of silently deciding differently.

## 4. Verification

Before finishing:

- Run typecheck
- Run linter
- Run relevant tests if they exist for the touched area
- Fix any errors introduced by your changes

## 5. Do NOT commit or push

Stop after implementation. Do not commit, do not push, do not open a PR.
The user reviews the diff manually first.

## 6. Summary

When done, output a summary with:

- **Branch name** created
- **Files changed** (list, with 1-line reason per file)
- **Acceptance criteria** — checklist showing which ones are satisfied and how
- **Deviations** — anything done differently from the ticket or Technical
  Notes, and why
- **Open questions / risks** — anything unsure about or that needs input
- **Not done** — any AC item that couldn't be completed, and why

Wait for review before proceeding further. If Linear MCP is connected, set
the ticket status to "In Progress" at the start and leave it there — do not
mark it "Done" or "In Review" yourself.
